cff-version: 1.2.0
title: "cite-or-abstain: an evaluation harness for citation grounding and abstention in clinical LLM outputs"
message: "If you use this software, please cite it as below."
type: software
authors:
  - given-names: "Carl Luis"
    family-names: "Pöhl"
    email: clpoehl@gmail.com
repository-code: "https://github.com/cl-poehl/cite-or-abstain"
license: MIT
version: 0.8.0
date-released: "2026-07-23"
keywords:
  - clinical-ai
  - llm-evaluation
  - hallucination
  - citation-grounding
  - abstention
  - medical-ai
abstract: >-
  cite-or-abstain scores language-model outputs against a categorical rubric: an actionable
  claim should either carry a verifiable citation or explicitly abstain. It classifies each
  output as cited, uncited-confident, uncited-hedged, or abstained, then verifies cited
  claims on two axes — a deterministic, location-aware passage match against a pinned corpus,
  and a narrow topical-alignment judge. The headline metric,
  coverage - lambda * confident_error_rate, penalises only the confident-error cell, so
  abstention is never punished and a fabricated citation is never scored a free zero.
  Citation verdicts separate demonstrated failure (fabricated, miscited) from inconclusive
  evidence (unlocated), so a matcher limitation is not misreported as a hallucination rate.
  The harness measures its own LLM judge against human labels (accuracy with Wilson intervals,
  Gwet's AC1, and a confusion matrix), and runs fully on-prem against any OpenAI-compatible
  server.
